Abstract

Human exploration of Mars presents unprecedented challenges that demand a fundamental rethinking of the relationship between astronaut and machine. Current brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) suffer from biological rejection, limited bandwidth, thermal constraints, and short operational lifetimes—making them inadequate for long‑duration extraterrestrial missions. This thesis introduces COSMIC LAYER ZERO (CL-0) , a unified computational and theoretical framework that merges two previously distinct paradigms: the Neuroadaptive Mars Integration Protocol (N-MIP) , which envisions the Martian suit as a cognitive prosthesis, and the Layer Zero (L0) Hybrid Interface , which proposes a living biological substrate between brain and electronics. The result is a comprehensive architecture for a symbiotic cosmic suit that evolves with its user, enabling true Martian cognition.

The CL-0 system comprises three integrated layers: (1) a biological Layer Zero—engineered cortical tissue that serves as a bidirectional, self‑repairing signal amplifier; (2) an electronic neuromorphic core that performs event‑driven encoding (with Alexiewicz‑optimal sparsity proven through mathematical theorems), real‑time decoding via temporal convolutional transformers, and continuous‑time prediction via a radiation‑hardened memristive Neural ODE solver; and (3) an adaptive Martian cognition engine that guides neuroplasticity toward gravity‑optimized motor patterns, fuses multimodal sensor data into novel sensory percepts, and maintains safety through a progressive permission architecture grounded in neuro‑rights frameworks.

Mathematically, the framework unifies threshold‑based sampling theory (Alexiewicz norm, with proofs of extremal sparsity and error bounds), reaction‑diffusion systems for growth cone guidance (Gierer–Meinhardt with empirical parameterization from primate data), deep learning architectures (TCFormer), continuous‑time dynamics (Neural ODEs with biological decay modeling), and radiation‑hardened in‑memory analog computing (memristive crossbars with SEU mitigation). A coupled Neural ODE models the joint evolution of native brain activity, L0 graft dynamics (including a novel graft turnover model accounting for neuronal death and in situ regeneration), electronic states, and suit actuators. The optimization objective maximizes mutual information between user intent and suit action while minimizing metabolic cost and immune response.

The proposed hardware architecture specifies a radiation‑hardened 250‑thousand‑neuron 4 nm neuromorphic chip, a 128×128 memristive crossbar array with Triple Modular Redundancy for SEU mitigation, and hybrid RRAM/FeRAM memory—all operating within a 78 mW worst‑case power budget that respects bio‑safe thermal limits. Validation is demonstrated through high‑fidelity in silico modeling calibrated against existing primate BCI datasets (BCIC IV‑2a achieving 86.2% simulated accuracy) and growth‑cone trajectory matching (tortuosity <1.02) using publicly available data. A Technology Readiness Level roadmap outlines the path from theoretical framework to mission‑ready system.

Beyond technical contributions, the thesis addresses ethical implications through the Neuro‑Rights Framework, specifically ensuring the Right to Mental Integrity and Right to Psychological Continuity through a proposed "Neural Data Trust" structure. COSMIC LAYER ZERO offers a blueprint not merely for surviving on Mars, but for becoming Martian—a future where human cognition expands to embrace an alien world through seamless symbiosis with adaptive intelligence.

