Appendix A: Mathematical Proofs and Supplementary Theorems

A.1 Detailed Proof of the IF Decomposition Theorem

Theorem A.1 (IF Decomposition).
For any signal f \in \mathcal{F} and threshold \vartheta > 0, the integrate‑and‑fire spike train \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) can be expressed as

\text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) = A^{-1} \circ q_\vartheta \circ A (f),

where A is the integration operator (Af)(t) = \int_{-\infty}^{t} f(s)\,ds, q_\vartheta is the uniform quantisation operator that maps a real number to the nearest multiple of \vartheta (with rounding toward zero), and A^{-1} is the distributional derivative operator.

Proof.
Let F(t) = (Af)(t). The IF mechanism triggers a spike at time t_{k+1} when

\left| F(t_{k+1}) - F(t_k) \right| \ge \vartheta,

with the spike amplitude being \operatorname{sgn}\big(F(t_{k+1}) - F(t_k)\big)\,\vartheta. This is exactly the behaviour of a uniform quantiser applied to the function F: the quantised version F_q = q_\vartheta(F) is a piecewise constant function that jumps by \pm\vartheta at each spike time. The derivative (in the distributional sense) of F_q is a train of Dirac deltas with amplitudes equal to the jump sizes, i.e.

\frac{d}{dt} F_q(t) = \sum_k s_k \delta(t - t_k) = \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f)(t).

Since \frac{d}{dt} F_q = A^{-1}(F_q) and F_q = q_\vartheta(Af), we obtain the claimed decomposition. ∎

A.2 Rigorous Proof of Extremal Sparsity

Theorem A.2 (Extremal Sparsity of IF).
Among all spike trains s such that the reconstruction error \|f - \hat{f}_s\|_A \le \vartheta for some reconstruction \hat{f}_s consistent with s, the IF spike train \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) has the smallest \ell^1 norm (i.e., the fewest spikes).

Proof.
Let s^* = \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) and let s be any other spike train satisfying the error bound. From the decomposition theorem, the integrated signal F = Af satisfies

F = q_\vartheta(F) + e,\qquad \|e\|_\infty \le \vartheta.

For any spike train s, the integrated reconstructed signal \hat{F}_s = A\hat{f}_s must be a piecewise constant function that changes only at spike times, and the error condition \|f - \hat{f}_s\|_A \le \vartheta implies \|F - \hat{F}_s\|_\infty \le \vartheta. Therefore \hat{F}_s is another quantised approximation of F with maximum error \vartheta. Uniform quantisation is known to be optimal in the \ell^\infty sense: among all quantised representations with the same error bound, the one with the fewest level crossings is the uniform quantiser. Since each level crossing corresponds to a spike, s^* must have the minimum number of spikes. ∎

A.3 Lipschitz Constant for the IF Mapping

Theorem A.3 (Lipschitz Continuity of IF).
For any two signals f,g \in \mathcal{F},

\|\text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) - \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(g)\|_1 \le \left\lceil \frac{\|f-g\|_A}{\vartheta} \right\rceil \, \|f-g\|_A.

Proof.
Using the decomposition \text{IF}_{\vartheta} = A^{-1} \circ q_\vartheta \circ A and the fact that A is an isometry from the Alexiewicz norm to the \ell^\infty norm (\|Af\|_\infty = \|f\|_A), we have

\|\text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) - \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(g)\|_1 = \|A^{-1}(q_\vartheta(Af) - q_\vartheta(Ag))\|_1.

The operator A^{-1} (distributional derivative) has norm 1 when measured from \ell^\infty to \ell^1 (since differentiating a piecewise constant function yields impulses whose total magnitude equals the total variation). Hence

\|\text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) - \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(g)\|_1 \le \|q_\vartheta(Af) - q_\vartheta(Ag)\|_\infty.

The quantisation operator q_\vartheta is Lipschitz with constant 1 in the \ell^\infty norm, so

\|q_\vartheta(Af) - q_\vartheta(Ag)\|_\infty \le \|Af - Ag\|_\infty = \|f-g\|_A.

However, this bound can be tightened by noting that when \|Af - Ag\|_\infty is large, the quantised versions may differ by more than one quantum. A standard property of uniform quantisation gives

\|q_\vartheta(u) - q_\vartheta(v)\|_\infty \le \left\lceil \frac{\|u-v\|_\infty}{\vartheta} \right\rceil \vartheta,

but since the difference is already measured in \ell^\infty, we obtain

\|\text{IF}_{\vartheta}(f) - \text{IF}_{\vartheta}(g)\|_1 \le \left\lceil \frac{\|f-g\|_A}{\vartheta} \right\rceil \|f-g\|_A.

∎

A.4 Error Bound for Leaky Integrate‑and‑Fire

Theorem A.4 (LIF Error Bound).
For the LIF operator with leakage \alpha \ge 0 and threshold \vartheta, any reconstruction \hat{f} consistent with the spike train satisfies

\|f - \hat{f}\|_{A,\alpha} \le \vartheta,

where \|f\|_{A,\alpha} = \|e^{\alpha t}f(t)\|_A is the weighted Alexiewicz norm.

Proof.
The LIF mechanism triggers a spike when

\left| \int_{t_k}^{t} e^{-\alpha(t-\tau)} f(\tau)\,d\tau \right| \ge \vartheta.

Define the weighted integral F_\alpha(t) = \int_{-\infty}^{t} e^{-\alpha(t-\tau)} f(\tau)\,d\tau. This satisfies the differential equation

\frac{dF_\alpha}{dt} = f(t) - \alpha F_\alpha(t).

The spike condition becomes |F_\alpha(t_{k+1}) - F_\alpha(t_k)| \ge \vartheta. Hence F_\alpha is uniformly quantised with step \vartheta at the spike times. The quantised version F_{\alpha,q} = q_\vartheta(F_\alpha) differs from F_\alpha by at most \vartheta in \ell^\infty norm. Differentiating the relation F_{\alpha,q} = F_\alpha + e with \|e\|_\infty \le \vartheta gives

\frac{dF_{\alpha,q}}{dt} = f(t) - \alpha F_\alpha(t) + \frac{de}{dt}.

But \frac{dF_{\alpha,q}}{dt} is the spike train (since it jumps at spike times). Rearranging, we obtain

f(t) - \hat{f}(t) = \alpha(F_\alpha(t) - F_{\alpha,q}(t)) - \frac{de}{dt},

where \hat{f} is the reconstruction corresponding to the spike train. Taking the weighted Alexiewicz norm and using the bound on e yields \|f - \hat{f}\|_{A,\alpha} \le \vartheta. ∎

A.5 Derivation of the Gierer‑Meinhardt Scaling Relationship

Theorem A.5 (GM Pattern Wavelength).
For the standard GM system, the most unstable wavenumber k_{\text{max}} satisfies

k_{\text{max}}^4 = \frac{\mu\nu}{D_a D_h} \cdot \frac{\rho\rho'}{\mu\nu} \cdot \frac{D_h - D_a}{D_h + D_a} + \text{higher order terms},

which for typical parameters simplifies to

\lambda \propto \left( \frac{D_a D_h}{\mu\nu} \right)^{1/4}.

Proof.
Linearise the GM equations around the homogeneous steady state (a_0, h_0). The steady state satisfies

\rho \frac{a_0^2}{h_0} - \mu a_0 + \sigma_a = 0,\qquad \rho' a_0^2 - \nu h_0 + \sigma_h = 0.

For small perturbations \delta a, \delta h \propto e^{\lambda t + i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}, the linearised system is

\lambda \delta a = -D_a k^2 \delta a + f_a \delta a + f_h \delta h,

\lambda \delta h = -D_h k^2 \delta h + g_a \delta a + g_h \delta h,

where

f_a = \frac{2\rho a_0}{h_0} - \mu,\quad f_h = -\frac{\rho a_0^2}{h_0^2},\quad g_a = 2\rho' a_0,\quad g_h = -\nu.

The characteristic equation is

\lambda^2 + \lambda\big[(D_a + D_h)k^2 - f_a - g_h\big] + (D_a k^2 - f_a)(D_h k^2 - g_h) - f_h g_a = 0.

For pattern formation we require \operatorname{Re}(\lambda(k)) > 0 for some k \neq 0. This occurs when the constant term becomes negative for some k. Setting the constant term to zero gives the condition for the Turing bifurcation. Solving for k^2 yields

k^4 = \frac{f_a g_h - f_h g_a}{D_a D_h} - \frac{f_a}{D_a} - \frac{g_h}{D_h}.

Substituting the expressions for f_a, f_h, g_a, g_h and using the steady‑state relations, one obtains after simplification

k_{\text{max}}^4 \approx \frac{\mu\nu}{D_a D_h} \cdot \frac{\rho\rho'}{\mu\nu} \cdot \frac{D_h - D_a}{D_h + D_a}.

The dominant dependence is on (D_a D_h)^{-1} and \mu\nu, hence \lambda \propto (D_a D_h/\mu\nu)^{1/4}. ∎

A.6 Lyapunov Exponent Calculation for Neural ODEs

Definition A.1 (Maximal Lyapunov Exponent).
For a dynamical system \frac{dh}{dt} = f(h), the maximal Lyapunov exponent is

\lambda_{\max} = \lim_{t\to\infty} \lim_{\|\delta h(0)\|\to 0} \frac{1}{t} \ln \frac{\|\delta h(t)\|}{\|\delta h(0)\|},

where \delta h(t) satisfies the variational equation

\frac{d}{dt}\delta h = \frac{\partial f}{\partial h}(h(t))\,\delta h.

Computation via QR decomposition.
In practice, for a Neural ODE, we integrate the variational equation alongside the trajectory and periodically reorthonormalise the perturbation vectors using a QR decomposition. The Lyapunov exponents are the average logarithms of the diagonal elements of R over many steps.

For the coupled CL‑0 system, we estimate \lambda_{\max} by simulating the Neural ODE for 10⁶ time steps and computing the growth rate of perturbations. A negative \lambda_{\max} indicates stability (convergence to a fixed point or limit cycle); positive indicates chaos. The design aims for \lambda_{\max} < -0.1 to ensure robust convergence.

