Appendix B: Gierer‑Meinhardt Numerical Methods and Parameter Sensitivity

B.1 Finite Difference Discretisation

The GM equations are discretised on a regular 2D grid with spacing \Delta x = \Delta y = 1\,\mu\text{m}. Time stepping uses an explicit Euler scheme with step \Delta t = 0.01\,\text{s} (ensuring stability). The Laplacian is approximated by the five‑point stencil:

\nabla^2 u_{i,j} \approx \frac{u_{i-1,j} + u_{i+1,j} + u_{i,j-1} + u_{i,j+1} - 4u_{i,j}}{(\Delta x)^2}.

The diffusion coefficients D_a, D_h are scaled appropriately for the chosen grid spacing.

B.2 Stability Constraints

For the explicit scheme, the time step must satisfy

\Delta t < \frac{(\Delta x)^2}{2\max(D_a, D_h)} \approx 5.5\times 10^{-5}\,\text{s}

if we use the physical diffusion values. To avoid excessively small time steps, we use a semi‑implicit method: treat diffusion implicitly and reaction explicitly (IMEX scheme). This allows \Delta t \approx 0.1\,\text{s} without instability.

B.3 Parameter Sensitivity Analysis

We performed a Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis by varying the parameters \rho_0, \rho_1, \mu, \nu within \pm20\% of their nominal values and observing the resulting pattern wavelength and growth cone turning angle. The results (1000 simulations) show that:

· Wavelength is most sensitive to \mu and \nu (exponents near 0.5 in log‑log plot).
· Turning angle is most sensitive to \rho_1 (gradient sensitivity).
· The system remains within acceptable bounds (\lambda variation <15\%) for all tested variations.

B.4 Calibration to Experimental Data

We used a method‑of‑moments approach to calibrate the GM parameters to the experimental patch spacing data from Bauer et al. (2015). For each parameter set, we simulated pattern formation and computed the dominant wavelength via Fourier analysis. The parameters were adjusted to minimise the mean squared error between simulated and experimental patch spacings across multiple cortical areas. The final values (Table 3.1) yield an R² of 0.97.

