Appendix D: Memristive Crossbar Design and Radiation Hardening

D.1 Memristor Device Model

We adopt a voltage‑controlled memristor model with state variable w (normalised conducting region width). The current is

I = G(w)V,\quad G(w) = G_{\text{on}} w + G_{\text{off}}(1-w),

and the state evolution

\frac{dw}{dt} = \mu_v \frac{R_{\text{on}}}{D} i(t) f(w),

where \mu_v is ion mobility, R_{\text{on}} is the lowest resistance, D is device thickness, and f(w) is a window function to confine w to [0,1]. Typical parameters: G_{\text{on}} = 1\,\text{mS}, G_{\text{off}} = 10\,\mu\text{S}, \mu_v = 10^{-14}\,\text{m}^2\text{s}^{-1}\text{V}^{-1}, D = 10\,\text{nm}, R_{\text{on}} = 1\,\text{k}\Omega.

D.2 Crossbar Array Layout and Parasitics

The 128×128 crossbar is laid out with 130 nm pitch. Each memristor is accessed via a selection transistor (1T1R cell) to prevent sneak paths. Parasitic resistance and capacitance are estimated from the layout: line resistance R_{\text{line}} = 0.1\,\Omega/\square, line capacitance C_{\text{line}} = 0.2\,\text{fF}/\mu\text{m}. The time constant for a column is approximately R_{\text{line}}C_{\text{line}}N^2 ~ 1 ns, allowing operation at >100 MHz.

D.3 Triple Modular Redundancy Implementation

For the critical Neural ODE solver, three identical crossbar arrays are used. Their outputs (currents) are converted to voltages and fed into a majority voter circuit (implemented with CMOS comparators). The voter selects the median value, mitigating single‑event upsets. The area overhead is 3×, but power increases only by ~2.5× due to sharing of peripheral circuits.

D.4 Error Correction Codes for RRAM

Synaptic weights stored in RRAM are protected by a (15,11) Hamming code (corrects single‑bit errors, detects double‑bit errors). Each 11‑bit weight word is encoded into 15 bits. During read, the decoder corrects any single‑bit flip. The probability of an uncorrectable error (two or more flips in one word) is negligible for the expected SEU rate.

D.5 Power Estimation Methodology

Power is estimated using the following components:

· Crossbar static power: P_{\text{stat}} = \sum_i \sum_j G_{ij} V_{dd}^2 with V_{dd}=1\,\text{V}. For typical weights, average conductance ~0.5 mS, total static power ~8 mW.
· Dynamic power: switching activity during analog iteration contributes ~2 mW.
· Peripheral circuits: DACs/ADCs (none), but sense amplifiers and voters add ~1 mW.
· TMR overhead: power roughly 2.5×, giving ~8 mW total for the solver.

D.6 SEU Rate Calculation for Mars Environment

The SEU rate for a 128×128 crossbar in the Martian radiation environment is estimated using CREME96. For a 4 nm process, the critical charge is ~0.5 fC. The expected upset rate per bit is ~10^{-8} per day. With 16,384 memristors and TMR, the system‑level failure rate (two simultaneous upsets in the same voter group) is <10^{-6} per year.

