Appendix E: Simulation Methodology and Extended Results

E.1 NeuroPixel Dataset Preprocessing

We used the publicly available dataset "pfc-1" from CRCNS.org, containing multi‑channel recordings from primate prefrontal cortex during a delayed response task. Data were:

· Downsampled to 1 kHz
· Spike‑sorted using KiloSort
· Segmented into 1‑second trials aligned to stimulus onset
· Normalised to zero mean and unit variance per channel

E.2 IF Encoding Simulation Code

The IF encoding was implemented in Python using NumPy and SciPy. For each signal segment, the integrated signal F(t) was computed via cumulative trapezoidal integration. Spike times were recorded whenever F(t) crossed a multiple of \vartheta from the previous spike. The threshold \vartheta was chosen to achieve a desired average spike rate (e.g., 20 Hz). Reconstruction used a kernel smoother (exponential kernel with time constant 20 ms) applied to the spike train.

E.3 Reconstruction Algorithms

For reconstruction from spike trains, we used optimal linear filtering (Wiener filter) assuming a known signal autocorrelation. The filter coefficients were computed from the training set and applied to the spike train convolved with a basis function (exponential or raised cosine).

E.4 Comparative Metrics Details

Van Rossum distance: spike trains convolved with e^{-t/\tau} (\tau=20 ms), then Euclidean distance computed. Victor‑Purpura distance: implemented with cost per spike shift = 1, cost per time shift = 0.05 ms⁻¹.

E.5 Growth Cone Simulation: GAN Architecture

The conditional GAN for gradient field design used:

· Generator: U‑Net with 4 down/up blocks, input: desired target positions (binary mask) and noise vector, output: 2D gradient field G(x,y).
· Discriminator: PatchGAN (70×70 patches) with spectral normalisation.
· Loss: LSGAN + L1 loss on trajectory tortuosity.

Training used 10,000 simulated trajectories from a biophysical growth cone model [Mortimer et al. 2009]. The generator was conditioned on the target location and produced gradients that, when fed into the growth cone simulator, yielded trajectories with tortuosity <1.02 in 95% of cases.

E.6 Digital Twin Simulation Parameters

The Neural ODE for the coupled system was implemented in PyTorch using the torchdiffeq library. Parameters:

· Solver: dopri5 (adaptive Runge‑Kutta 4/5) with tolerance 1e‑6
· Time span: 15 years simulated with 1‑day steps (but internal adaptive steps)
· Biological decay: \delta_0 = 0.01 day⁻¹, \delta_1 = 0.1 day⁻¹, \tau = 30 days
· Turnover events every 18 months, lasting 7 days, with 20% of neurons replaced
· Immune response model: R_{\text{immune}} = \int (c_{\text{IL-6}} + c_{\text{TNF-α}})\,dt with cytokine dynamics coupled to graft size

