Appendix F: Neural ODE Adjoint Method Implementation

F.1 Derivation of Adjoint Equations for the Coupled System

The coupled system is \frac{d\mathbf{S}}{dt} = \mathbf{F}(\mathbf{S}, t, \Theta). To compute gradients of a loss L(\mathbf{S}(T)) with respect to parameters \Theta, we introduce the adjoint \mathbf{a}(t) = \partial L / \partial \mathbf{S}(t). The adjoint satisfies the ODE

\frac{d\mathbf{a}}{dt} = -\mathbf{a}(t)^\top \frac{\partial \mathbf{F}}{\partial \mathbf{S}}.

For the decomposed system (cortex, L0, elec, suit), the Jacobian \partial \mathbf{F}/\partial \mathbf{S} is block‑diagonal with cross‑coupling terms, but the adjoint equation still holds.

F.2 Numerical Integration Schemes

We use the Dormand‑Prince (dopri5) method for both forward and backward integration. The forward solution is stored at checkpoints (every 100 steps) to allow reverse integration without storing the entire trajectory.

F.3 Automatic Differentiation vs. Adjoint Method

We compared the adjoint method with automatic differentiation (AD) through the ODE solver. For a 15‑year simulation with ~10⁶ internal steps, AD required >100 GB memory, while the adjoint method used <1 GB. The adjoint method was also 5× faster in wall‑clock time.

F.4 Stability and Convergence

The adjoint method is mathematically equivalent to backpropagation through the ODE solver. We verified convergence by comparing gradients computed via adjoint and via finite differences (perturbing each parameter by 1e‑4). The relative error was <1e‑3 for all parameters.

